es. In this rigorous and illuminating work, Matt Bakker, an economic sociologist, examines how these migrant remittances-the resources of some of the world's least affluent people-have come to be seen in recent years as a fundamental contributor to development in the migrant-sending states of the Global South. This book analyzes how the connection between remittances and development was forged through the concrete political and intellectual practices of policy entrepreneurs within a variety of institutional settings, from national government agencies and international development organizations to nongovernmental policy foundations and think tanks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEconomic developmentzMexico. 0aEconomic development. 0aEmigrant remittanceszMexico. 0aEmigrant remittanceszNorth America. 0aEmigrant remittances. 0aEmigration and immigrationxEconomic aspects. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh  a21st century finance.  aamerican dollar.  abusiness economics.  abusiness finance.  abusiness.  acapitalism.  adeveloping countries.  aeconomic development.  aeconomics of emigration.  aeconomics of immigration.  afinancial democracy.  aglobal economics.  aglobal finance.  aimmigrants sending money home.  amigrant remittances.  amigrants sending money home.  amigrants with money.  amigration and money.  amigration.  amoney and power.  amoney matters.  amoney.  anational development.  apolitics of measurement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz9780520285